The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 ONGC feels subsidy pressure

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Oct. 19: The Oil and Natural Gas Corporation (ONGC) today reported an almost flat net profit at Rs 4,173.98 crore in the second quarter ended September 30, mainly due to a 78 per cent jump in its subsidy payout.

 ONGCs net profit increased from Rs 4,138.25 crore in the second quarter of 2005-06 to Rs 4,173.98 crore this fiscal, a company press release said here. It shelled out Rs 5,032 crore by way of discounts to refiners to compensate them for revenue loss on LPG and kerosene in the July-September quarter. 

 Revenues stood at Rs 15,008.26 crore in the July-September quarter against Rs 13,543.31 crore in the corresponding period of the previous year.

 ONGC has reported an 11.2 per cent increase in net profit at Rs 8,293 crore in the first half of the current fiscal against Rs 7,457 crore in the same period of the previous year. Turnover increased from Rs 23,682 crore last year to Rs 28,823 crore.

 The companys board has appointed a sub-committee of directors to finalise the allotment of bonus shares by October 30. The shareholders are expected to receive the bonus shares by the second half of next month. 




